I did have this fellow, Mike Dorsey, who inherited some money
an esteemed attorney had introduced me and thought, why don't you get in with Mike and see if we can develop that idea.

We had to make another model.

And finally, Dorst didn't want any more.

By then, I was in the mill business as an estimator in the wood business.
And it wasn't, I was not in a necessary in a hurry.
Nobody else was making any tennis rackets.
So, but I always fool around with it and come up with a new model and I test it out, take it out to the courts.
And one of the biggest problems was the cutting of the strings because of the sharpness of the edges.
And that was very difficult to resolve.
And then they come up with plastic strips and inserts with a nice black insert, by the way, which is the way they came out later on.
And then Mr. Carson, who was a developer,
Al?
Al Carstens.
Carstens.
Let me see if I'm picking this stuff up.

He had plenty of successful developments in Teo.

And in fact, his father, who was 70 some odd years old, also thought the idea was great.
He must have talked to him about it, you know.
And he made us a model, the finest model that was ever made.
It was made by Al Carson's father.
He could get the holes cleaned.
Nobody else could.
The little birds were not there.
No, the little birds were not there.
He was from the old country.
And, excuse me, and, but there was something came up.
They did not want their father to do any more of those things.
I heard, I got that impression.
Don't bother, you know, I was really enthused when I saw that model that he made.
He had no problem doing it.
But I think a family matter came up and they didn't want their 77-year-old father working in a wood shop or wherever he was all day.
So that thing kind of fell through.
But we did make some models.
We played with it.
And I was very impressed with the power of it.
I could see that it was going to be a much superior racket to wood as soon as I got the strings and about an ounce or a half an ounce overweight.
and the balance corrected, I knew it was going to be a much better...
I could see my serve was much harder right away.
I served more aces, so I knew the idea was right.
It was just a question of the technology and engineering.
How did you take up tennis as a young man?
What caused you to turn to tennis instead of soccer?
The usual story.
Ice skating.
I had a curvature of the spine and my doctor said I had to do something to some exercise.
But that was one part.
The other part was my dad had bought me a violin and I
I really was not too crazy about my violin lessons.
So I traded in the violin for a tennis racket.

And the first year I won the Junior Championships of Schweidnitz, which is not very much, but we had four courts and I won the Junior Championship and from then on there was no stopping me in the game.
I mean, you start out winning your first
tennis tournament, and the same happened to me in skiing.
I won my first slalom, giant slalom.
So, you know, you can't stop somebody when you get that kind of a start.
Would it be all right to continue on a tennis tournament?
Okay, more on a tennis tournament.
Because it really was responsible for kind of major reconnection.
Yeah.

But for then the next several years this went on.
We formed a family corporation.
Cheryl was married by that time, first married, to a young man who worked for a big advertising agency in San Francisco.
And when Cheryl and Dave split up and he went around the world that way and she went the other way, he went to Australia.
and we sent him off with, we had some beautiful stationary printed and the company name and a cable address and all this kind of thing.
Dennis, I think,

was probably, he wanted to do all of those things, but he always kind of hung back on the exposure part of it, all these trappings, you know, so he might want to talk about his feelings on that score.
The part I wanted to get at was how we then moved, because of all this tennis activity, when we did make a major move then, it was to
another setting, which was the racket.
I just wanted to kind of bring that into some chronology.
Because it was a major part of our energy for about five or six years when we were first married.
Now that's the energy level up here.
On the feeling level, when I look back on it, I can see how we devoted so much conversation, energy, emotional effort, everything was going into that tennis racket.
along with other stuff.

What does that mean?
We never got around to, I'm sorry you missed some of this.
Yeah, I want to

How do you feel about that or something else?
I think you're absolutely right.
Exactly what it was.
Concentrate on that one project.
And if it wasn't that project, then the next project was the development of the Racquet Club.
And then there was always another, you know, subsequent, whatever it was.
Yeah, but look at all these successful millionaires in this country do the same thing.
They have no time for their love life and they get divorced.
So it is a, but it did serve a dual purpose, you know.
I said I did it because I thought I could become independently wealthy or get a decent job anyway.
What I was bringing up was then how we got from, because of the tennis racket, the interest in tennis, when we did make a move, was how we got to play in the long run.
So it did help in the long run.
Yes.

took the list, probably, that we had of the members, and got enough money from the bank, who happens to be a tennis player in our club.

Vineyards.

kind of that influenced you?
How much do you want to do?
What do you want to do, Dennis, to drive yourself crazy?

Oh, yes.
That was a very traumatic thing.
So he wanted me to play in his alumni tournament at Stanford.
And we were winning.
We were doing fine.
We got to the finals.
And we had to wait an hour or so.
I was a little tired, and I walked around the clubhouse that they had.
And I looked up, and I see that they have a plaque for all the winners every year.
And I knew.
And when I came back down, I couldn't hit a ball.
Because I didn't want my name and his name up there forever and ever.
And have him find out that I didn't want to dishonor him.
That's the way I was.
I was totally froze.
I could not hit the simplest tennis ball.
We lost the final.
So the name didn't go up.
